DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines the economic and philosophical foundations of diminishing
marginal utility as applied to wealth versus income. The literature reveals a
systematic distinction often overlooked in utilitarian theory: marginal utility
behaves differently for flow variables (income) versus stock variables (wealth/
assets). Classical utility theory, stemming from Bernoulli (1738), established
that money exhibits diminishing marginal utility - each additional dollar provides
less satisfaction than the previous one. However, modern behavioral economics
reveals this principle requires refinement when distinguishing income from wealth.

The key insight is that wealth accumulation beyond a security threshold serves
different functions than income. While income addresses ongoing consumption needs
with relatively high marginal utility, accumulated assets primarily serve as
insurance against uncertainty (precautionary motive), positional signaling, or
bequest motives - all of which exhibit lower marginal utility. Recent work on
positional goods (Walasek et al. 2017, Shahar 2017) demonstrates that wealth
often functions as a relative rather than absolute good, diminishing its marginal
utility for welfare. The precautionary savings literature (Horioka & Ventura 2020,
Painter et al. 2021) shows that households accumulate wealth primarily for
insurance, not consumption, which fundamentally changes marginal utility calculations.

The sufficientarian literature (Hassoun 2021, Huseby 2020, Bossert et al. 2021)
introduces the concept of sufficiency thresholds - levels above which distribution
matters less morally. This provides philosophical grounding for the empirical
observation that marginal utility of wealth drops sharply after basic security
needs are met, while income continues to bear higher marginal utility for ongoing
needs.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses the central question of whether utilitarian giving
norms should focus on income (flow) or wealth (stock) thresholds. The literature
provides both theoretical and empirical support for distinguishing these variables:
beyond a security threshold, assets exhibit lower marginal utility than income
due to their role in insurance, status-seeking, and bequest rather than direct
consumption. This asymmetry suggests that asset-based giving norms may better
capture utilitarian obligations than income-based norms like the 10% pledge.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Few papers directly compare marginal utility of income versus wealth within the
same framework. The connection between sufficientarian thresholds and precautionary
wealth motives remains under-theorized. Limited philosophical attention to how
positional aspects of wealth affect utilitarian calculations. The role of wealth
thresholds in determining charitable obligations is rarely addressed explicitly.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Synthesize the precautionary savings literature with sufficientarian philosophy
to argue for wealth-based thresholds. Connect positional goods theory to the
low marginal utility of excess assets. Contrast the consumption-focused marginal
utility of income with the insurance/status-focused marginal utility of wealth.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Classical diminishing marginal utility: 6 papers - Marginal utility decreases with wealth but doesn't distinguish income from assets
- Precautionary wealth theory: 4 papers - Assets primarily serve insurance function with low marginal utility
- Positional goods theory: 4 papers - Wealth serves relative status function, reducing absolute marginal utility
- Sufficientarianism: 4 papers - Above threshold, distribution matters less; supports differential treatment of assets
====================================================================
}

